    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It makes it clear that the method accepts null values, and that if you override the method, you should also accept null values.</p>\n\n<p>It also serves as a hint for code analyzers like <a href=\"http://findbugs.sourceforge.net/\">FindBugs</a>. For example, if such a method dereferences its argument without checking for null first, FindBugs will emit a warning.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1292103,
      "reputation" : 9246,
      "user_id" : 1243996,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 97,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Ic3YC.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Adam Sznajder",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1243996/adam-sznajder"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 96,
    "last_activity_date" : 1629527348,
    "last_edit_date" : 1629527348,
    "creation_date" : 1356731866,
    "answer_id" : 14076324,
    "question_id" : 14076296,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This annotation is commonly used to eliminate <code>NullPointerExceptions</code>. <code>@Nullable</code> says that this parameter might be <code>null</code>. A good example of such behaviour can be found in <a href=\"https://github.com/google/guice/wiki/UseNullable\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Google Guice</a>. In this lightweight dependency injection framework you can tell that this dependency might be <code>null</code>. If you would try to pass <code>null</code> without an annotation the framework would refuse to do it's job.</p>\n<p>What is more, <code>@Nullable</code> might be used with <code>@NotNull</code> annotation. Here you can <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/nullable-and-notnull-annotations.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">find</a> some tips on how to use them properly. Code inspection in IntelliJ checks the annotations and helps to debug the code.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 44379,
      "reputation" : 14798,
      "user_id" : 130224,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 84,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dde3b34749219173bbf3e07ca710eccc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "reprogrammer",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/130224/reprogrammer"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 20,
    "last_activity_date" : 1484979921,
    "last_edit_date" : 1484979921,
    "creation_date" : 1356733965,
    "answer_id" : 14076610,
    "question_id" : 14076296,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Different tools may interpret the meaning of <code>@Nullable</code> differently. For example, the <a href=\"https://checkerframework.org/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Checker Framework</a> and <a href=\"http://findbugs.sourceforge.net/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">FindBugs</a> handle <code>@Nullable</code> <a href=\"https://checkerframework.org/manual/#findbugs-nullable\" rel=\"noreferrer\">differently</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
