      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Using Optional as a replacement of <code>if</code> statement this is an anti-pattern, because it unnecessarily creates a new object.  Creator of Optional mentions this here: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Ej0sss6cq14?start=1664&amp;end=1800\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">youtube.com/embed/Ej0sss6cq14?start=1664&amp;end=1800</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6077039,
      "reputation" : 1124,
      "user_id" : 4744055,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/rsxdO.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Manabu Tokunaga",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4744055/manabu-tokunaga"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1585415529,
    "creation_date" : 1585415529,
    "answer_id" : 60904114,
    "question_id" : 14076296,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Granted, there are definitely different thinking, in my world, I cannot enforce \"Never pass a null\" because I am dealing with uncontrollable third parties like API callers, database records, former programmers etc... so I am paranoid and defensive in approaches. Since you are on Java8 or later there is a bit cleaner approach than an <code>if</code> block.</p>\n\n<pre><code>public String foo(@Nullable String mayBeNothing) {\n   return Optional.ofNullable(mayBeNothing).orElse(\"Really Nothing\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You can also throw some exception in there by swapping <code>.orElse</code> to \n<code>orElseThrow(() -&gt; new Exception(\"Dont' send a null\"))</code>.</p>\n\n<p>If you don't want to use @Nullable, which adds nothing functionally, why not just name the parameter with <code>mayBe...</code> so your intention is clear.</p>\n"
  } ],
